young American artists who took up Cézanne’s cause after they discovered him in Paris. It is also the story of the discerning early American collectors of his work—Leo and Gertrude Stein, the Havemeyers, and John Quinn, among others—many of whom made their first purchases from Cézanne’s wily dealer Ambroise Vollard in Paris, or from the dealer Alfred Stieglitz in New York, and of the beginning of the famous collection of Dr. Albert C. Barnes. Each chapter is illustrated not only with Cézanne’s works but also with portraits of collectors and critics and with previously unpublished pages from diaries, dealers’ ledgers, and Cézanne’s own correspondence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aArt Amateur Magazine.  aArt and Criticism.  aCaillebotte, Gustave.  aCassatt, Mary.  aChild, Theodore.  aColumbian Exposition (1893), Chicago.  aDurand-Ruel Galleries.  aDurand-Ruel, Paul.  aFabbri, Egisto.  aFarmyard.  aFry, Roger.  aGeffroy, Gustave.  aHallowell, Sara.  aHarper’s Weekly.  aHavemeyer, H. O. and L.  aHermitage Museum, Leningrad.  aMarks, Montague.  aMilk-can and Apples.  aRodin, Auguste 12.  aSantayana, George.  aSeurat, Georges.  aShchukin, Sergei.  aSignac, Paul.  aTanguy, père.  aVie Artistique, La.  aVollard, Ambroise.  aWorld’s Fair (Chicago).08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252285?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252285/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR